+# 💡 Why I Built This
+
+I wanted to understand what tools like Nmap are actually doing under the hood, rather than just running them. Building a SYN scanner meant learning raw packet crafting with Scapy instead of relying on the OS socket stack for handshakes; building the CVE correlation layer meant dealing with rate limits, unreliable third-party APIs, and the fact that version-string matching against a public vulnerability database is messier than it sounds (see the OpenSSH patch-suffix handling in `cve_lookup.py`).
+
+**What I learned building it:**
+- Why real scanners use threading/async carefully — a naive sequential scan across even 1000 ports is unacceptably slow, but too many concurrent SYN packets on a low-latency network also produces false positives from dropped responses.
+- Banner-based fingerprinting is fragile — port number alone is a bad signal for what's actually running on a host, which is what motivated the exposure-classification bug fix documented below.
+- Async work needs to be genuinely decoupled from the scan loop — the CVE correlation step originally risked blocking scan output if not handled carefully.
+
+This is a recon tool, not a finished product — see the Roadmap and Positioning sections below for what it's intentionally *not* trying to be yet.
+
+---
+
+# ⚔️ ReconForge vs Nmap
+
+The obvious question: why build this when Nmap exists? Short answer — I'm not trying to replace it.
+
+| | Nmap | ReconForge |
+|---|---|---|
+| Maturity | 25+ years, industry standard | Personal project, actively learning |
+| Port scanning techniques | Dozens (SYN, FIN, XMAS, ACK, idle scan, etc.) | SYN scan + protocol-aware UDP probing |
+| OS fingerprinting | Deep TCP/IP stack fingerprinting (`-O`) | TTL-based heuristic only |
+| Scripting/extensibility | NSE (huge script library) | Not yet — plugin architecture is on the roadmap |
+| CVE correlation | Via NSE scripts (`vulners`, `vuln` category) | Built-in, async, non-blocking by default |
+| Output | Human-readable, XML, grepable | JSON-first, designed for pipeline integration |
+| Purpose here | Production-grade, battle-tested tool | Learning exercise in how scanners actually work internally |
+
+ReconForge isn't trying to out-perform Nmap on breadth or reliability — it's a from-scratch implementation of the concepts Nmap is built on (raw packet crafting, banner fingerprinting, exposure correlation), with a couple of opinionated defaults Nmap doesn't have out of the box, like async CVE correlation and structured JSON as the primary output rather than an add-on flag.
